<Layout title="How to Sell a Jointly Owned Property in Queensland | Daniel Gierach Property" description="A guide to selling property co-owned by two or more people in Queensland, tenants in common, joint tenancy, when co-owners disagree, and how to manage the process." draft={draft}>

<script type="application/ld+json">
{
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "FAQPage",
  "mainEntity": [
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What is the difference between joint tenancy and tenants in common in Queensland?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Joint tenants own the property as a single entity, if one owner dies, their share automatically passes to the surviving owner(s) regardless of what the will says. Tenants in common each own a defined share (which can be unequal), and each person's share can be independently sold, transferred, or left in a will. Co-ownership structure significantly affects how the property can be sold."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Can one co-owner force the sale of a jointly owned property in Queensland?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Yes. Under Queensland law (Property Law Act 2023), a co-owner can apply to the Supreme Court for an order for the sale or partition of jointly owned property if co-owners cannot agree. This is known as a statutory partition action. It is a last resort, most disputes are resolved through negotiation or mediation before reaching this stage."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Can one co-owner sell their share of a property without the other's consent?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "A tenant in common can generally sell their individual share to a third party without the other co-owner's consent, though this is rarely practical since most buyers are not interested in purchasing a part-share of a property. Joint tenants cannot sell their share independently, all joint tenants must agree to any sale of the property."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What happens if co-owners disagree about the sale price?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Disagreements about price are common in co-owned property sales. An independent formal property valuation, agreed to by all co-owners, is the most effective way to establish a neutral reference point for negotiations. If agreement cannot be reached, mediation through a qualified property mediator is usually faster and cheaper than court proceedings."
      }
    }
  ]
}
</script>

<article style="background:var(--color-surface-0);min-height:100vh;">

